57
00:02:47,061 --> 00:02:49,062
Thank you for coming by,
gentlemen.

58
00:02:49,065 --> 00:02:50,764
No problem.
So what's up?

59
00:02:50,767 --> 00:02:54,234
Well, it was the two of you who
found Amy Farrah Fowler for me.

60
00:02:54,237 --> 00:02:56,203
Now that I'm looking
for my next girlfriend,

61
00:02:56,204 --> 00:02:59,774
it seemed only logical that I
employ your services once again.

62
00:02:59,775 --> 00:03:02,576
Y-You sure you're up for that?
She did hurt you.

63
00:03:02,578 --> 00:03:05,478
Oh, no, it's all right.
I think of my time with Amy

64
00:03:05,481 --> 00:03:09,115
as a stick of Fruit Stripe gum:
sweet and enjoyable at first,

65
00:03:09,118 --> 00:03:12,786
but ultimately
a flavorless lump of sadness.

66
00:03:13,788 --> 00:03:15,589
You're not wrong
about Fruit Stripe.

67
00:03:15,590 --> 00:03:18,958
I-I was always
a Hubba Bubba man. Mm.

68
00:03:18,960 --> 00:03:22,095
Hubba Bubba over Dubble Bubble?
You're crazy.

69
00:03:22,097 --> 00:03:25,198
Hey, the jaw wants
what it wants.

70
00:03:25,201 --> 00:03:26,900
Gentlemen!

71
00:03:26,903 --> 00:03:28,803
Oh, right, uh, girlfriend. Okay.

72
00:03:28,804 --> 00:03:30,404
But what are you
looking for?

73
00:03:30,405 --> 00:03:31,772
All I'm looking for

74
00:03:31,773 --> 00:03:34,375
is an educated, intelligent
woman who shares my interests

75
00:03:34,376 --> 00:03:36,376
while retaining
her own unique point of view.

76
00:03:36,379 --> 00:03:37,544
She should be kind,

77
00:03:37,547 --> 00:03:38,679
patient,

78
00:03:38,680 --> 00:03:40,047
and most important,

79
00:03:40,049 --> 00:03:44,184
unable to imagine life
without me by 10:00 tonight.

80
00:03:44,186 --> 00:03:46,186
Isn't that
a little unreasonable?

81
00:03:46,189 --> 00:03:47,655
All right, fine,
she doesn't need

82
00:03:47,656 --> 00:03:50,857
her own point of view.
Now, chop-chop.

83
00:03:51,959 --> 00:03:53,861
Come on, Amy,
show us the dress.

84
00:03:53,863 --> 00:03:55,261
Okay.

85
00:03:55,263 --> 00:03:59,867
But I'm really stepping outside
of my comfort zone here.

86
00:04:05,774 --> 00:04:07,107
Uh...

87
00:04:07,109 --> 00:04:10,210
I don't think any of your
comfort zones are showing.

88
00:04:10,213 --> 00:04:11,711
Yeah,

89
00:04:11,714 --> 00:04:13,914
it's your third date— maybe
you could go more sexy.

90
00:04:13,915 --> 00:04:18,018
Well, some people think
the sexiest organ is the brain.

91
00:04:18,020 --> 00:04:19,987
No one ever bought me drinks
at a bar

92
00:04:19,989 --> 00:04:23,023
because my brain
just popped out of my shirt.

93
00:04:23,025 --> 00:04:24,758
Do you have any heels
higher than this?

94
00:04:24,761 --> 00:04:25,926
He's pretty tall.

95
00:04:25,927 --> 00:04:27,294
Ooh.
Ooh, tall!

96
00:04:27,295 --> 00:04:29,429
Finally some details
about this mystery man.

97
00:04:29,431 --> 00:04:31,165
Yeah, come on,
tell us more.

98
00:04:31,167 --> 00:04:33,633
Well, I told you his name
and that he's tall.

99
00:04:33,636 --> 00:04:34,902
What more do you need?

100
00:04:34,903 --> 00:04:36,169
Did you kiss him yet?

101
00:04:36,172 --> 00:04:38,605
Just a little peck on the lips.

102
00:04:42,410 --> 00:04:44,544
Well, we're your best friends—
give us one more detail

103
00:04:44,547 --> 00:04:46,147
and we promise
we'll leave you alone.

104
00:04:46,148 --> 00:04:47,948
Fine. Um...

105
00:04:47,950 --> 00:04:49,783
he's British.

106
00:04:52,386 --> 00:04:55,355
All right, that is a juicy one.

107
00:04:55,357 --> 00:04:57,857
All right, where is
Tall British Dave taking you?

108
00:04:57,859 --> 00:05:00,561
Tea and basketball?

109
00:05:00,563 --> 00:05:02,797
To that new Italian place
on Walnut.

110
00:05:02,799 --> 00:05:03,931
Oh, nice.

111
00:05:03,932 --> 00:05:05,766
I'm gonna go look for other shoes.
Good luck.

112
00:05:05,768 --> 00:05:08,201
I threw out all my tall ones
when I married Leonard.

113
00:05:10,371 --> 00:05:11,739
Hey, you want

114
00:05:11,741 --> 00:05:14,008
to swing by that place tonight
and get a look at this guy?

115
00:05:14,009 --> 00:05:16,277
We don't even know what time
they're gonna be there.

116
00:05:16,278 --> 00:05:17,610
I'll just call the restaurant,

117
00:05:17,612 --> 00:05:19,379
pretend I'm Amy
and check the reservation.

118
00:05:19,381 --> 00:05:21,849
Damn, you're sneaky.

119
00:05:21,850 --> 00:05:24,117
Yeah, but I'm little,
so it's adorable.

120
00:05:27,121 --> 00:05:29,989
I think the quickest way
to find you a new girlfriend

121
00:05:29,992 --> 00:05:33,460
is just to get you on every
dating Web site out there.

122
00:05:33,461 --> 00:05:34,794
Are you sure?

123
00:05:34,797 --> 00:05:37,198
I've heard that on those
sites, often when you think

124
00:05:37,200 --> 00:05:39,732
you're corresponding with someone,
it's actually a computer program

125
00:05:39,734 --> 00:05:41,768
pretending to be
a real person.

126
00:05:41,770 --> 00:05:45,306
And you're afraid
it'll do a better job than you?

127
00:05:45,307 --> 00:05:47,474
Excuse me.

128
00:05:47,475 --> 00:05:48,475
No one does a better job

129
00:05:48,477 --> 00:05:50,311
pretending to be a person
than I do.

130
00:05:51,412 --> 00:05:54,581
Siri comes close,
but I know more jokes.

131
00:05:54,583 --> 00:05:57,083
If you don't want to
use dating Web sites,

132
00:05:57,085 --> 00:05:58,419
what do you suggest?

133
00:05:58,420 --> 00:06:00,920
Off the top of my head?
Uh, prospective women

134
00:06:00,922 --> 00:06:03,390
weed themselves out
in a battle of wits

135
00:06:03,391 --> 00:06:04,924
until only one champion remains,

136
00:06:04,927 --> 00:06:07,895
she shows up at my door flush
with the thrill of victory,

137
00:06:07,896 --> 00:06:11,965
and then sits quietly by my side
while I watch Daredevil.

138
00:06:11,967 --> 00:06:15,268
You seriously think women
would fight for you?

139
00:06:15,270 --> 00:06:19,405
People compete for jobs
and trophies— why not me?

140
00:06:19,407 --> 00:06:21,941
He's right— he knows
a lot of jokes.

141
00:06:23,177 --> 00:06:25,612
Yeah— no, but it is
basic human nature.

142
00:06:25,614 --> 00:06:29,415
If we present him as a prize,
maybe they would.

143
00:06:29,417 --> 00:06:31,117
Well, he's smart,

144
00:06:31,119 --> 00:06:32,886
he's a respected
scientist...

145
00:06:32,888 --> 00:06:36,790
And I have
the soulful eyes of a cow.

146
00:06:38,859 --> 00:06:40,927
I don't know
if I'd say you...

147
00:06:40,929 --> 00:06:42,730
Oh.

148
00:06:43,698 --> 00:06:45,032
I have an idea.

149
00:06:45,033 --> 00:06:47,801
What if we put a post
on Craigslist that says:

150
00:06:47,802 --> 00:06:50,703
"World-class Caltech physicist
seeking girlfriend.

151
00:06:50,705 --> 00:06:52,038
"If interested,

152
00:06:52,040 --> 00:06:55,342
solve the following puzzles
for a chance to meet him."

153
00:06:55,343 --> 00:06:57,044
Oh, we'll make the puzzles
extremely challenging

154
00:06:57,045 --> 00:06:59,078
to eliminate
unworthy candidates.

155
00:06:59,080 --> 00:07:01,448
Oh, we could set it up
like a scavenger hunt where

156
00:07:01,450 --> 00:07:04,285
the last puzzle gives the winner
Sheldon's contact information.

157
00:07:04,287 --> 00:07:06,720
Well, this is actually an
interesting social experiment.

158
00:07:06,722 --> 00:07:08,588
I'm a little jealous of the
people who get to do it.

159
00:07:08,590 --> 00:07:09,590
Me, too.

160
00:07:09,592 --> 00:07:11,424
And we've seen the prize.

161
00:07:15,463 --> 00:07:17,765
I don't understand why we're
leaving so early for the movie.

162
00:07:17,766 --> 00:07:19,967
Oh, I forgot to tell you—
we're gonna meet up

163
00:07:19,968 --> 00:07:22,095
with Bernadette to spy
on Amy and her date.

164
00:07:22,119 --> 00:07:22,836
What?

165
00:07:22,838 --> 00:07:24,405
I don't want to do that.

166
00:07:24,407 --> 00:07:26,205
What, and you think I
want to see a documentary

167
00:07:26,208 --> 00:07:28,174
about aluminum can
recycling?

168
00:07:28,177 --> 00:07:29,576
This is the movie

169
00:07:29,578 --> 00:07:32,513
Big Soda doesn't
want you to see.

170
00:07:32,514 --> 00:07:35,982
No, it's the movie your wife
doesn't want you to see.

171
00:07:36,850 --> 00:07:38,318
So you're actually okay

172
00:07:38,321 --> 00:07:40,254
with invading
your friend's privacy?

173
00:07:40,256 --> 00:07:42,588
You're not curious
who she's out with?

174
00:07:42,590 --> 00:07:43,924
Not really.

175
00:07:43,926 --> 00:07:47,126
But you're curious
about aluminum cans.

176
00:07:48,129 --> 00:07:50,364
You're a weird
little guy.

177
00:07:53,133 --> 00:07:56,102
That's it. The Sheldon Cooper
Girlfriend Challenge

178
00:07:56,105 --> 00:07:58,571
is officially alive.

179
00:07:58,573 --> 00:08:00,306
Congratulations.
This is exciting.

180
00:08:00,309 --> 00:08:01,475
Right now,

181
00:08:01,477 --> 00:08:03,677
somewhere, a woman
is dividing the atomic weight

182
00:08:03,679 --> 00:08:06,213
of the best noble gas
by the number of colors

183
00:08:06,215 --> 00:08:09,215
in the oldest national flag still in use...
W— then using

184
00:08:09,217 --> 00:08:11,617
that number as the average speed
to calculate the travel time

185
00:08:11,619 --> 00:08:13,619
from Mordor to the Shire.
And...

186
00:08:13,621 --> 00:08:15,922
taking her first step
towards a lifetime

187
00:08:15,924 --> 00:08:19,693
of laughter,
love and, best of all, rules.

188
00:08:19,694 --> 00:08:22,720
I-I hope we didn't make
the puzzles too hard.

189
00:08:22,722 --> 00:08:26,033
Well... if she can solve them,
it'll prove she's intelligent,

190
00:08:26,035 --> 00:08:27,835
tenacious and...
so socially awkward

191
00:08:27,836 --> 00:08:30,504
she has nothing better to do
on a Saturday night.

192
00:08:32,273 --> 00:08:35,175
Golly, she sounds
too good to be true.

193
00:08:37,579 --> 00:08:39,513
This is fun.
I haven't dated much

194
00:08:39,514 --> 00:08:41,248
since my divorce.

195
00:08:41,249 --> 00:08:43,316
Well, I'm having
a good time, too.

196
00:08:43,318 --> 00:08:46,452
If you don't mind me asking, why
did you and your wife split up?

197
00:08:46,455 --> 00:08:49,056
Oh, you know how it is—
we wanted different things.

198
00:08:49,057 --> 00:08:50,324
I wanted children,

199
00:08:50,326 --> 00:08:53,627
and she wanted a pastry chef
named Jean-Philippe.

200
00:08:53,629 --> 00:08:56,230
Oh, I'm... I'm so sorry.

201
00:08:56,231 --> 00:08:57,864
No, it's-it's fine.
It's why I left England.

202
00:08:57,866 --> 00:08:59,600
It reminded me
too much of her.

203
00:08:59,601 --> 00:09:04,437
Cold, gloomy and easily accessed
by a Frenchman through a tunnel.

204
00:09:05,907 --> 00:09:08,207
Hey. So, where are they?

205
00:09:08,210 --> 00:09:10,344
Across the street,
in the left window.

206
00:09:10,345 --> 00:09:12,012
Oh, damn it,

207
00:09:12,013 --> 00:09:13,580
we should have brought
binoculars.

208
00:09:13,581 --> 00:09:16,016
Right here.

209
00:09:16,018 --> 00:09:18,552
We just happen to have those
in the car?

210
00:09:18,553 --> 00:09:20,086
Kinda. Before I met Howie,

211
00:09:20,089 --> 00:09:22,556
I liked to keep close tabs
on my boyfriends.

212
00:09:22,557 --> 00:09:24,023
By stalking them?

213
00:09:24,026 --> 00:09:26,125
No. Stalkers
are creepy.

214
00:09:26,128 --> 00:09:28,028
I'm just a harmless little girl

215
00:09:28,029 --> 00:09:30,763
with military-grade
spy equipment.

216
00:09:31,699 --> 00:09:33,066
Oh, there he is.

217
00:09:33,068 --> 00:09:34,401
He's cute, right?

218
00:09:34,403 --> 00:09:36,769
Yeah!
Can I see?

219
00:09:36,772 --> 00:09:39,720
What, now you're interested?
You didn't even want to come.

220
00:09:39,721 --> 00:09:43,577
I know, but you guys make being
a crappy friend look fun.

221
00:09:43,579 --> 00:09:45,678
Fine.

222
00:09:45,681 --> 00:09:47,914
Yeah, okay, I see him.

223
00:09:47,917 --> 00:09:49,516
It looks like
they're having a nice time.

224
00:09:49,518 --> 00:09:50,817
I wish I could hear
what they're saying.

225
00:09:50,820 --> 00:09:52,085
Yeah, I should've brought

226
00:09:52,087 --> 00:09:53,253
my parabolic microphone.

227
00:09:53,254 --> 00:09:55,321
Your what?
Nothing. Not important.

228
00:09:56,758 --> 00:09:58,191
So you've never
been married?

229
00:09:58,194 --> 00:10:01,327
No. I mean,
to be completely honest, I've...

230
00:10:01,330 --> 00:10:03,696
I've only been
in one long-term relationship.

231
00:10:03,699 --> 00:10:05,032
Oh. What happened with that?

232
00:10:05,033 --> 00:10:06,600
That's a good question.

233
00:10:11,519 --> 00:10:12,787
After five years,

234
00:10:12,788 --> 00:10:15,523
it was just feeling like
more work than it should be.

235
00:10:15,524 --> 00:10:16,657
Oh, that's too bad.

236
00:10:16,658 --> 00:10:18,258
Was he a neurobiologist
like you?

237
00:10:18,260 --> 00:10:20,595
No. He's a theoretical physicist

238
00:10:20,596 --> 00:10:23,531
at Caltech.

239
00:10:23,532 --> 00:10:26,466
I love teaching math, but
that would be my dream job.

240
00:10:26,469 --> 00:10:27,734
What's his focus?

241
00:10:27,736 --> 00:10:31,071
Um... used to be string theory,
now it's dark matter.

242
00:10:31,074 --> 00:10:33,139
But... let's
not discuss Sheldon.

243
00:10:33,142 --> 00:10:35,042
Let's get back to you.

244
00:10:35,043 --> 00:10:38,512
Wait, you're not talking
about Dr. Sheldon Cooper?

245
00:10:39,781 --> 00:10:43,116
I'm trying not to.

246
00:10:43,951 --> 00:10:45,018
Do you know him?

247
00:10:45,020 --> 00:10:47,455
No, but I've followed
his work for years.

248
00:10:47,456 --> 00:10:48,623
He's a rock star.

249
00:10:48,624 --> 00:10:50,423
You've got to
tell me about him.

