dull and needy, eh?

296
00:12:56,346 --> 00:12:57,745
Not to cast aspersions,

297
00:12:57,748 --> 00:13:02,051
but I can't shake a stick around
here without hitting that.

298
00:13:05,888 --> 00:13:08,523
You know, I once
drove 500 miles

299
00:13:08,526 --> 00:13:11,493
to hear him speak
at Stanford.

300
00:13:11,494 --> 00:13:14,495
I have a DVD of that lecture.

301
00:13:14,498 --> 00:13:16,498
Really? Wasn't it great?

302
00:13:16,499 --> 00:13:20,134
Not as a Valentine's
present, no.

303
00:13:20,137 --> 00:13:21,869
Well, the next time
you watch it,

304
00:13:21,872 --> 00:13:23,638
I'm the bloke who
asked the question

305
00:13:23,641 --> 00:13:26,642
that he said was
stupid and obvious.

306
00:13:26,643 --> 00:13:29,945
It was the nicest thing
he said to anyone there.

307
00:13:29,946 --> 00:13:31,779
That's, um, terrific.

308
00:13:31,782 --> 00:13:34,649
Listen, I'm-I'm kind of tired.
Can we call it a night?

309
00:13:34,652 --> 00:13:37,052
Oh, gosh. Sorry,
I've just spent the whole night

310
00:13:37,053 --> 00:13:39,020
talking about your ex-boyfriend.

311
00:13:39,023 --> 00:13:40,422
I'm such an idiot.

312
00:13:40,423 --> 00:13:42,358
No, you're not.

313
00:13:42,359 --> 00:13:45,293
Well, maybe not an idiot,
but certainly not as smart as...

314
00:13:45,296 --> 00:13:47,061
someone we won't mention.

315
00:13:47,064 --> 00:13:49,064
Thank you.
But you said

316
00:13:49,066 --> 00:13:51,300
you might introduce me to him—
I'm free on Thursday.

317
00:13:52,869 --> 00:13:54,436
Hey, hey,
they're leaving.

318
00:13:54,437 --> 00:13:57,272
What? Here,
give me, give me.

319
00:13:57,273 --> 00:13:59,874
Oh, my God. Oh, my God,
they're coming right towards us.

320
00:13:59,877 --> 00:14:02,945
We got to get out of here.
Okay. Well, wait, what about Leonard?

321
00:14:02,946 --> 00:14:05,980
He and his tiny bladder
can take the bus!

322
00:14:10,186 --> 00:14:11,387
Oh, no!

323
00:14:15,825 --> 00:14:18,159
She just hit my car!

324
00:14:18,162 --> 00:14:20,229
What are you guys
doing here?

325
00:14:20,230 --> 00:14:24,199
Oh! Hey, Ames!
What are you doing here?

326
00:14:25,100 --> 00:14:26,435
What happened?

327
00:14:27,269 --> 00:14:28,504
OMG!

328
00:14:28,505 --> 00:14:30,439
Aren't you
Leonard Hofstadter?

329
00:14:30,441 --> 00:14:31,940
Yeah.

330
00:14:31,941 --> 00:14:34,676
I saw you speak at Stanford
with Sheldon Cooper!

331
00:14:34,677 --> 00:14:37,345
Amy, can you believe it?
It's Dr. Leonard Hofstadter!

332
00:14:39,349 --> 00:14:41,517
No. Pinch me.

333
00:14:41,518 --> 00:14:44,253
It's an absolute pleasure to meet you.
Can I shake your hand?

334
00:14:44,254 --> 00:14:46,254
I don't know if you want
to do that— I was just...

335
00:14:46,257 --> 00:14:47,822
Okay, never mind.

336
00:14:48,657 --> 00:14:50,725
Amy, I'm never washing
this hand again.

337
00:14:50,728 --> 00:14:53,394
You really should.

338
00:14:54,564 --> 00:14:57,231
60 seconds.

339
00:14:57,234 --> 00:14:58,499
This is not looking good.

340
00:14:58,502 --> 00:15:00,469
One minute is
a long time.

341
00:15:00,470 --> 00:15:03,504
I've been telling women that
for 20 years.

342
00:15:06,176 --> 00:15:08,911
45.
45 seconds is

343
00:15:08,912 --> 00:15:11,245
plenty of time for a woman
to walk through that door

344
00:15:11,248 --> 00:15:12,614
and fall in love with me.

345
00:15:12,615 --> 00:15:15,716
You know, probably half that
if I break out the old cow eyes.

346
00:15:16,552 --> 00:15:18,019
30 seconds.

347
00:15:18,022 --> 00:15:19,488
Uh-oh.

348
00:15:19,489 --> 00:15:22,090
What if it's Jennifer Lawrence?

349
00:15:22,091 --> 00:15:23,358
What?

350
00:15:23,359 --> 00:15:25,661
Oh, that last Hunger Games
was not my cup of tea.

351
00:15:25,662 --> 00:15:28,564
You thought she was great
in X-Men.

352
00:15:28,566 --> 00:15:29,998
Oh, fine— I won't shut my heart

353
00:15:29,999 --> 00:15:31,600
to the love
of Jennifer Lawrence.

354
00:15:32,835 --> 00:15:35,883
Guys, 15 seconds.
Maybe she's waiting to show up

355
00:15:35,883 --> 00:15:37,673
at the last possible moment.

356
00:15:37,675 --> 00:15:39,041
Sounds like a drama queen.

357
00:15:39,042 --> 00:15:42,911
Oh, no.
It is Jennifer Lawrence.

358
00:15:43,645 --> 00:15:44,446
Five...

359
00:15:44,447 --> 00:15:45,814
four...

360
00:15:45,816 --> 00:15:47,416
three...

361
00:15:47,417 --> 00:15:49,250
two...

362
00:15:49,253 --> 00:15:50,652
one.

363
00:15:55,057 --> 00:15:56,959
That's too bad.

364
00:15:56,960 --> 00:15:59,460
Maybe we did make the test
too difficult.

365
00:15:59,462 --> 00:16:01,263
I don't think it matters.
Look, Sheldon,

366
00:16:01,264 --> 00:16:04,199
I believe when the time is right
for you to meet someone,

367
00:16:04,201 --> 00:16:05,533
it'll just happen.

368
00:16:05,536 --> 00:16:08,202
Okay? Not because of
a test or a Web site,

369
00:16:08,205 --> 00:16:10,404
but because...

370
00:16:10,407 --> 00:16:13,642
We are the dreamers of dreams!

371
00:16:19,382 --> 00:16:21,950
It's an actual girl,
and she's really pretty.

372
00:16:21,951 --> 00:16:23,784
Answer it!

373
00:16:23,787 --> 00:16:25,254
All right.

374
00:16:31,460 --> 00:16:32,793
Can I help you?

375
00:16:32,796 --> 00:16:36,064
Um, a-are you the physicist that
placed the ad on Craigslist?

376
00:16:36,066 --> 00:16:37,199
Yes.

377
00:16:37,201 --> 00:16:39,301
Hi. I'm Vanessa Bennett.

378
00:16:39,302 --> 00:16:41,168
Sorry it took a while
for me to get here.

379
00:16:41,171 --> 00:16:42,671
I was stuck in this
boring symposium

380
00:16:42,672 --> 00:16:45,273
on atomic spectroscopy
when I came across your ad,

381
00:16:45,276 --> 00:16:46,774
and it saved my night.

382
00:16:46,777 --> 00:16:48,576
The puzzles were...
were really fun.

383
00:16:48,579 --> 00:16:50,678
I've never had
to translate Klingon

384
00:16:50,681 --> 00:16:53,882
into ancient Sanskrit before.

385
00:16:53,883 --> 00:16:55,584
Well...

386
00:16:55,585 --> 00:16:58,787
careful, hmm, it's addictive.

387
00:16:58,788 --> 00:17:02,790
Chija'e'vlKub je.

388
00:17:04,928 --> 00:17:07,194
Or, as they say
in Sanskrit...

389
00:17:08,096 --> 00:17:11,066
Ahm asman matey-bee
ta-teyva.

390
00:17:11,067 --> 00:17:15,037
And just like that, you're
a Klingon-Sanskrit junkie.

391
00:17:15,038 --> 00:17:18,006
Anyway, I-I just... I knew
I had to meet the person

392
00:17:18,008 --> 00:17:20,174
responsible for such
a brilliant idea.

393
00:17:20,176 --> 00:17:22,710
And I don't need to tell you,
there aren't a lot of men

394
00:17:22,712 --> 00:17:26,515
who love physics, archaic languages
and flags of the world.

395
00:17:26,517 --> 00:17:29,183
I am a bit of a unicorn.

396
00:17:29,185 --> 00:17:31,153
Well, you certainly seem

397
00:17:31,154 --> 00:17:33,689
like a special lady,
uh, but as you know,

398
00:17:33,691 --> 00:17:36,357
you missed the deadline,
so thanks for playing.

399
00:17:43,633 --> 00:17:45,834
How could you
send her away?

400
00:17:45,835 --> 00:17:48,002
She was late.

401
00:17:48,005 --> 00:17:49,037
And...

402
00:17:49,038 --> 00:17:51,206
she found
atomic spectroscopy boring.

403
00:17:51,208 --> 00:17:54,910
Well, I wouldn't coitus her
with your genitals.

